    conceptId: REFLC,
    subjectSlug: 'physics',
    familyKind: 'core_explanation',
    gradeBand: GradeBand.HIGH,
    content:
      'The Law of Reflection states ∠i = ∠r, where BOTH the angle of incidence and the angle of reflection are measured from the NORMAL — the line perpendicular to the surface at the point where light strikes it — never from the surface itself. This matters because the normal is unambiguous (exactly one perpendicular direction exists at any point on a flat surface), while "the angle from the surface" depends entirely on which direction along the surface you happen to pick as reference. If a ray strikes a mirror making 35° with the surface, the angle from the normal (90° − 35° = 55°) is what the Law of Reflection actually uses — not 35°. Whether a surface produces a clear reflected IMAGE (specular reflection) or merely scatters light diffusely without forming an image depends entirely on surface roughness relative to the wavelength of light (roughly 400–700 nm): a mirror, with irregularities smaller than about λ/10 (≈ 40-70 nm), has all its microscopic facets essentially parallel, so every tiny reflection obeys ∠i = ∠r in the SAME overall direction, producing a coherent image; ordinary white paper, with irregularities of 10-100 micrometres (thousands of wavelengths), still obeys the Law of Reflection at every individual microscopic facet, but those facets point in wildly different directions, scattering the reflected light diffusely in all directions — visible from any angle, but forming no coherent image.',
