    content:
      'A natural but wrong reference point: measuring the angle of incidence and reflection from the SURFACE itself, rather than from the normal — writing "∠i = 35°" when a ray makes 35° with the mirror surface. This is genuinely wrong, not just a different convention: draw the geometry carefully and the normal, being perpendicular to the surface, is 90° from it; a ray making 35° with the surface therefore makes 90° − 35° = 55° with the normal — that 55° is the true angle of incidence used in the Law of Reflection, not 35°. If you tried to measure everything from the surface instead, the only way "35° in equals 35° out" would give consistent physical predictions is if the reflected ray traveled directly along the surface itself (0° from the normal) — which is physically impossible for ordinary reflection. The normal is the correct reference precisely because it\'s UNAMBIGUOUS — there\'s exactly one perpendicular direction at any point on a flat surface — while "the angle from the surface" depends entirely on which direction along that (potentially oddly-tilted) surface you arbitrarily choose to measure from. Second, equally natural trap: expecting ANY smooth-looking surface — a glossy magazine cover, a sheet of white paper — to form a clear reflected image, since "smooth" intuitively suggests "mirror-like." It doesn\'t work that way: a white sheet of paper genuinely obeys the Law of Reflection (∠i = ∠r) at every microscopic patch of its surface, exactly like a mirror does, but paper\'s surface irregularities (roughly 10–100 micrometres) are THOUSANDS of times larger than the wavelength of visible light (400-700 nm), so each tiny facet points in a completely different direction, scattering reflected light everywhere (diffuse reflection) — you can see the paper from any angle, but no coherent image forms. A mirror\'s surface irregularities, by contrast, are smaller than roughly λ/10 (about 40-70 nm), so essentially all its microscopic facets point the same way, and every reflection travels in the same overall direction (specular reflection), producing the clear image you actually see. Both surfaces obey the exact same Law of Reflection at the microscopic level; the difference in surface roughness relative to the wavelength of light is what determines whether the macroscopic result is a coherent image or scattered, image-free glow.',
