    content:
      'A natural but wrong picture: imagining the prism somehow ADDS or CREATES the colors seen in the spectrum, as if white light going in were genuinely colorless and the prism painted it. Newton settled this definitively in 1666: pass white light through a first prism to get the familiar rainbow spectrum, block every color except one (say, isolated red), then pass ONLY that red through a second prism — no new colors appear, just red, further deflected. If the first prism had genuinely CREATED new colors from colorless light, the second prism should create yet more new colors from the isolated red — but it doesn\'t, because white light was never colorless to begin with: it\'s a superposition of ALL visible frequencies simultaneously, and the prism\'s only job is to spatially SEPARATE those pre-existing frequencies by refracting each one by a slightly different amount, never to generate or change any frequency itself. Second, equally natural but backwards trap: reasoning that violet light, having a SHORTER wavelength, must somehow "fit through" the glass more easily and therefore bend LESS. It bends MORE, not less. The refractive index for violet (n ≈ 1.53) is measurably larger than for red (n ≈ 1.51); a larger refractive index means light travels SLOWER inside the glass (since v = c/n), and by Snell\'s Law, more slowing at the refracting surface produces MORE bending, not less — wavelength itself doesn\'t directly determine bending, the speed change (captured by n) does. Violet, with the larger n and greater slowdown, is deviated by the LARGEST angle in a prism; red, with the smaller n, is deviated the LEAST — giving the familiar VIBGYOR order, with violet at the most-bent edge of the spectrum and red at the least-bent edge, exactly opposite to the "shorter wavelength, less bending" intuition.',
