    conceptId: POLR,
    subjectSlug: 'physics',
    familyKind: 'core_explanation',
    gradeBand: GradeBand.HIGH,
    content:
      'Polarization is direct proof that light is a TRANSVERSE wave, not a longitudinal one — because polarization means the E-field oscillates in a specific plane that is PERPENDICULAR to the direction light travels, and only a transverse oscillation even HAS a perpendicular plane to restrict; a longitudinal wave (like sound) oscillates parallel to its direction of travel, with no perpendicular plane at all, so it simply cannot be polarized. Think of passing a rope through a fence with vertical slats: wiggling the rope in all directions, only the up-down (vertical) oscillations pass through — this only works because the rope oscillates transversely (side to side relative to its length), never for a longitudinal wiggle (toward-away from the fence, which the slats couldn\'t select between at all). A genuinely counterintuitive but experimentally solid result: two crossed polarizers (oriented 90° apart) transmit zero light — but inserting a THIRD polarizer BETWEEN them at 45° actually INCREASES the transmitted intensity from exactly zero up to I₀/8, rather than blocking even more light as intuition might suggest. This happens because each polarizer doesn\'t just passively filter existing light — it actively RE-DEFINES the polarization state of whatever passes through: light polarized at 0° hits the intermediate 45° polarizer and comes out newly polarized at 45° (a completely different state than before), which the final 90° polarizer can then partially transmit (cos²45° = 50% of what reaches it), where it previously would have blocked the original 0°-polarized light completely.',
