    familyKind: 'core_explanation',
    gradeBand: GradeBand.HIGH,
    content:
      'Hamilton\'s principal function S is NOT simply "the action integral computed for a given path" — it is something more general: the Hamilton-Jacobi equation determines S(q,α,t) as a FUNCTION of coordinates and constants of motion α, valid independent of whether any specific trajectory is already known. S satisfies ∂S/∂t+H(q,∂S/∂q,t)=0 as a partial differential equation, and this holds regardless of whether you already know the trajectory — S is genuinely the SOLUTION to this PDE, not simply the number you get by evaluating the action integral ∫L dt along one specific already-known path. Thinking "I\'ll integrate L dt to get S" undersells the actual mathematical object: while S does reduce to the action along the ACTUAL classical trajectory once everything is solved, the Hamilton-Jacobi APPROACH treats S as an unknown function to be solved for via the PDE first — the trajectory itself is then extracted afterward from S, essentially inverting the usual order of "find the trajectory, then compute the action." A second, separate point: having multiple coordinates does NOT automatically mean you can always separate variables in the Hamilton-Jacobi equation — writing S=S₁(q₁)+S₂(q₂)+... is not a universal trick that always works. Separability requires SPECIFIC conditions on the Hamiltonian itself: H must genuinely be separable in each coordinate for the additive-S ansatz to succeed. Cyclic coordinates always separate cleanly (their corresponding S-term is simply linear in that coordinate, proportional to the conserved conjugate momentum), but for non-cyclic coordinates, separability is a genuine PROPERTY of the specific Hamiltonian in question — never guaranteed just because multiple coordinates happen to be present. The precise mathematical conditions under which full separation is possible are captured by Liouville-separability and the Stäckel conditions — formal criteria that must actually be checked, not simply assumed, before attempting an additive-separation ansatz.',
