    content:
      'Some students say "S is just the action integral; I can compute it separately," reasoning "I\'ll integrate L dt to get S" — treating S as simply a number you obtain by plugging a known trajectory into the action integral. This significantly undersells what Hamilton\'s principal function S actually is within the Hamilton-Jacobi framework. S is genuinely a FUNCTION S(q,α,t) of the coordinates q and a set of constants of motion α — and the Hamilton-Jacobi equation, ∂S/∂t+H(q,∂S/∂q,t)=0, is a partial differential equation that determines this function, valid and solvable regardless of whether you already know the trajectory ahead of time. This is a genuinely different mathematical approach from "integrate L dt along a known path": in the Hamilton-Jacobi method, S is treated as an unknown function that must be solved for via this PDE FIRST, and only afterward is the actual trajectory extracted from the solved S — essentially the reverse order from the naive picture of "find the trajectory, then compute its action." It is true that, once everything is solved, S does reduce along the genuine classical trajectory to the ordinary action integral — but the entire power and purpose of the Hamilton-Jacobi approach is that it lets you find S (and hence the trajectory) WITHOUT needing to already know the trajectory in advance, which is precisely why the method is useful for finding trajectories in the first place, not merely a repackaging of an already-known answer. A second, entirely separate and equally significant error: assuming that having multiple coordinates automatically means you can always separate the Hamilton-Jacobi equation into independent pieces, saying "if there are multiple coordinates, you can always separate them," and simply writing something like S=S₁(q₁)+S₂(q₂) as if this always works as a matter of course. This is false — separability is not automatic or guaranteed merely because a system happens to have multiple coordinates. Separability requires SPECIFIC structural conditions to hold on the Hamiltonian H itself: H genuinely must be separable in each coordinate individually for the additive-S ansatz (S=ΣᵢSᵢ(qᵢ)) to actually work as a valid solution method. There is one reliable and always-true exception: CYCLIC coordinates always separate cleanly, because the corresponding piece of S for a cyclic coordinate is simply linear in that coordinate (proportional to its conserved conjugate momentum) — this case is guaranteed. But for NON-cyclic coordinates, separability is a genuine, nontrivial PROPERTY of the specific Hamiltonian under consideration — it is never automatically guaranteed just because the system happens to have several coordinates present. The precise formal conditions under which full separation is actually possible are captured by what are called Liouville-separability and the Stäckel conditions — specific, checkable mathematical criteria that must genuinely be verified for the particular Hamiltonian at hand, never simply assumed to hold as a general rule just because an additive-separation ansatz looks superficially plausible.',
